04178nam a22005535i 9780889207707DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20061996xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892077077 a10.51644/97808892077072doi  a(DE-B1597)667463  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBV5083b.H66 1996eb 7aREL0470002bisacsh04a248.2/21 aHorne, James R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMysticism and Vocation /cJames R. Horne. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (120 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEditions SR ;v1800tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tMysticism and Vocational Choice -- tMoral Perfection and Mysticism -- tPublic Criteria of Vocational Choice -- tPrivate Criteria of Vocational Choice -- tTaking Vocational Choices Seriously -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex -- tSeries Published by Wilfrid Laurier University Press for the Canadian Corporation for Studies in Religion/ Corporation Canadienne des Sciences Religieuses0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe tend to think that a person who is both reasonable and moral can have a good life. What constitutes a life that is not only good but superlative, or even “marvellous” or “holy”? Those who have such lives are called sages, heroes or saints, and their lives can display great integrity as well as integration with a transformative “Spiritual Presence.” Does it follow that saints are perfect people? Is there a common vision that impels them to seek holiness? In a controversial interpretation of mysticism Horne suggests that there is no single formula for the meaning of life and no one story that displays it to us. Mysticism, rather than being just a visionary perception, then becomes a problem-solving process that brings about a creative transformation of the personality at a critical stage in life. He suggests also that saints may be imperfect morally and describes true saints as double-minded: they are serious in a playful way. Mysticism and Vocation illuminates our understanding of saintly lives by explicating their mystical characteristics and extending discussions of mysticism to explain its role in active lives. In discussing important decisions that go beyond conventional morality, it adds to recent philosophical arguments by Charles Taylor, Alasdair MacIntyre, Iris Murdoch, Bernard Williams and others to the effect that morality should be defined more broadly to deal with the human condition. This book will be of interest to students of philosophy and religious studies, in both graduate and undergraduate programs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMysticism. 0aVocation (in religious orders, congregations, etc.). 4aPhilosophy. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Mysticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920770740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889207707423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889207707/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles